ChatGPT said:

Sure! Heres an updated version of your HTML+JS that:

  • Shows clear status messages at every step

  • Logs detailed errors in the browser console

  • Works better for mobile devices (with user prompts)

  • Adds timeouts for MQTT connection failure

  • Includes comments for clarity

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Send Location to AWS IoT</title>
  <script src="https://sdk.amazonaws.com/js/aws-sdk-2.814.0.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/paho-mqtt/1.1.0/mqttws31.min.js"></script>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; padding: 20px; }
    #status { margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h2> Sending Your Location to AWS IoT</h2>
  <p id="status">Starting...</p>

  <script>
    const REGION = "us-east-1";
    const IDENTITY_POOL_ID = "us-east-1:018326cf-26a9-4a3e-88e4-d64a4b61bdc2";
    const IOT_ENDPOINT = "a85vmpn2frq7e-ats.iot.us-east-1.amazonaws.com";

    function updateStatus(msg) {
      document.getElementById("status").textContent = msg;
      console.log(msg);
    }

    AWS.config.region = REGION;
    AWS.config.credentials = new AWS.CognitoIdentityCredentials({
      IdentityPoolId: IDENTITY_POOL_ID
    });

    updateStatus("Requesting AWS credentials...");
    AWS.config.credentials.get(function(err) {
      if (err) {
        updateStatus("Error getting AWS credentials: " + err.message || err);
        console.error("Cognito error:", err);
        return;
      }

      updateStatus("AWS credentials obtained.");

      const creds = AWS.config.credentials;
      const clientId = "client-" + Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000);

      // Paho MQTT client for WebSocket connection
      const mqttClient = new Paho.MQTT.Client(
        IOT_ENDPOINT,
        443,
        "/mqtt",
        clientId
      );

      const connectOptions = {
        useSSL: true,
        timeout: 5,
        mqttVersion: 4,
        onSuccess: () => {
          updateStatus("Connected to AWS IoT. Requesting location...");
          if (!navigator.geolocation) {
            updateStatus("Geolocation is not supported by your browser.");
            return;
          }

          navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
            (position) => {
              const payload = {
                lat: position.coords.latitude,
                lon: position.coords.longitude,
                time: new Date().toISOString()
              };
              const message = new Paho.MQTT.Message(JSON.stringify(payload));
              message.destinationName = "mobile/location";
              mqttClient.send(message);
              updateStatus(" Location sent to AWS IoT!");
              console.log("Published payload:", payload);
            },
            (geoErr) => {
              updateStatus("Geolocation error: " + geoErr.message);
              console.error("Geolocation error:", geoErr);
            },
            { enableHighAccuracy: true, timeout: 10000, maximumAge: 0 }
          );
        },
        onFailure: (err) => {
          updateStatus(" MQTT connection failed: " + JSON.stringify(err));
          console.error("MQTT connection failed:", err);
        },
        useSSL: true,

        // NOTE: The Paho MQTT JS client does NOT support AWS SigV4 auth out of the box.
        // Using AWS temporary credentials directly here will likely fail.
        // To fix this, you must generate a signed URL or use AWS IoT SDK v2/v3.
        userName: creds.accessKeyId,
        password: creds.sessionToken
      };

      mqttClient.connect(connectOptions);
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Important notes:

  • This still may not work fully because Paho MQTT client does not handle AWS Signature Version 4 authentication needed for AWS IoT WebSocket connections automatically.

  • To properly connect, youd either:

    • Use the AWS IoT Device SDK for JavaScript (v2 or v3), which handles signing and authentication properly, or

    • Manually generate a signed WebSocket URL with AWS SigV4 (which is non-trivial in pure client JS).

What to do now debugging steps:

  1. Open your browser console (F12 or equivalent) and check for errors or logs

    • Look for connection failure errors or exceptions logged by console.error.

  2. Try adding extra event handlers to log connection issues:
    Add this after mqttClient creation to catch more events:

js
mqttClient.onConnectionLost = function(responseObject) {
  updateStatus("MQTT connection lost: " + (responseObject.errorMessage || "Unknown error"));
  console.error("MQTT connection lost:", responseObject);
};

mqttClient.onMessageArrived = function(message) {
  console.log("MQTT message arrived:", message.payloadString);

  1. Use AWS IoT Device SDK for JavaScript (v2 or v3) instead of Paho
    The AWS SDK handles the necessary signing and authentication automatically, and is the recommended way to connect from browsers.

Quick example using AWS IoT Device SDK v2 (CDN version):

html
<script src="https://unpkg.com/aws-iot-device-sdk-v2/browser/aws-iot-sdk.min.js"></script>
<script>
  // ... your Cognito setup code ...

  AWS.config.credentials.get(async function(err) {
    if (err) {
      updateStatus("Error getting credentials: " + err.message);
      return;
    }
    updateStatus("AWS credentials obtained.");

    const clientId = "client-" + Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000);

    const client = new awsIot.device({
      region: REGION,
      credentials: AWS.config.credentials,
      clientId: clientId,
      endpoint: IOT_ENDPOINT,
      protocol: 'wss'
    });

    client.on('connect', function() {
      updateStatus("Connected to AWS IoT.");

      navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(position => {
        const payload = {
          lat: position.coords.latitude,
          lon: position.coords.longitude,
          time: new Date().toISOString()
        };
        client.publish('mobile/location', JSON.stringify(payload), {}, err => {
          if (err) {
            updateStatus("Publish error: " + err.message);
            console.error(err);
          } else {
            updateStatus(" Location sent to AWS IoT!");
          }
        });
      }, geoErr => {
        updateStatus("Geolocation error: " + geoErr.message);
      });
    });

    client.on('error', function(err) {
      updateStatus("Connection error: " + err);
      console.error(err);
    });
  });
</script>

To do that with your current setup (Paho MQTT client), you need to:

  1. Subscribe to the topic after successful connection

  2. Add an event handler for incoming messages (onMessageArrived)

  3. Display received messages in a visible area on your page

Heres an updated snippet with those features added:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Send & Receive Location on AWS IoT</title>
  <script src="https://sdk.amazonaws.com/js/aws-sdk-2.814.0.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/paho-mqtt/1.1.0/mqttws31.min.js"></script>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; padding: 20px; }
    #status { margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em; }
    #messages { margin-top: 20px; border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 10px; max-height: 200px; overflow-y: auto; }
    .message { margin-bottom: 8px; padding: 6px; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h2> Sending & Receiving Messages with AWS IoT</h2>
  <p id="status">Starting...</p>

  <h3>Incoming Messages on <code>mobile/location</code>:</h3>
  <div id="messages">(No messages yet)</div>

  <script>
    const REGION = "us-east-1";
    const IDENTITY_POOL_ID = "us-east-1:018326cf-26a9-4a3e-88e4-d64a4b61bdc2";
    const IOT_ENDPOINT = "a85vmpn2frq7e-ats.iot.us-east-1.amazonaws.com";

    function updateStatus(msg) {
      document.getElementById("status").textContent = msg;
      console.log(msg);
    }

    function addMessage(msg) {
      const container = document.getElementById("messages");
      const div = document.createElement("div");
      div.className = "message";
      div.textContent = msg;
      container.appendChild(div);

      // Scroll to bottom so latest message is visible
      container.scrollTop = container.scrollHeight;
    }

    AWS.config.region = REGION;
    AWS.config.credentials = new AWS.CognitoIdentityCredentials({
      IdentityPoolId: IDENTITY_POOL_ID
    });

    updateStatus("Requesting AWS credentials...");
    AWS.config.credentials.get(function(err) {
      if (err) {
        updateStatus("Error getting AWS credentials: " + err.message || err);
        console.error("Cognito error:", err);
        return;
      }

      updateStatus("AWS credentials obtained.");

      const creds = AWS.config.credentials;
      const clientId = "client-" + Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000);

      const mqttClient = new Paho.MQTT.Client(
        IOT_ENDPOINT,
        443,
        "/mqtt",
        clientId
      );

      mqttClient.onConnectionLost = function(responseObject) {
        updateStatus("MQTT connection lost: " + (responseObject.errorMessage || "Unknown"));
        console.error("Connection lost:", responseObject);
      };

      mqttClient.onMessageArrived = function(message) {
        const topic = message.destinationName;
        const payload = message.payloadString;
        addMessage(`[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] Topic: ${topic}  Message: ${payload}`);
        console.log("Received message:", topic, payload);
      };

      const connectOptions = {
        useSSL: true,
        timeout: 5,
        mqttVersion: 4,
        onSuccess: () => {
          updateStatus("Connected to AWS IoT. Subscribing to topic and sending location...");

          // Subscribe to topic to receive messages
          mqttClient.subscribe("mobile/location", {
            qos: 0,
            onSuccess: () => updateStatus("Subscribed to topic mobile/location"),
            onFailure: (err) => updateStatus("Subscribe failed: " + JSON.stringify(err))
          });

          if (!navigator.geolocation) {
            updateStatus("Geolocation is not supported by your browser.");
            return;
          }

          navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
            (position) => {
              const payload = {
                lat: position.coords.latitude,
                lon: position.coords.longitude,
                time: new Date().toISOString()
              };
              const message = new Paho.MQTT.Message(JSON.stringify(payload));
              message.destinationName = "mobile/location";
              mqttClient.send(message);
              updateStatus(" Location sent to AWS IoT!");
              console.log("Published payload:", payload);
            },
            (geoErr) => {
              updateStatus("Geolocation error: " + geoErr.message);
              console.error("Geolocation error:", geoErr);
            },
            { enableHighAccuracy: true, timeout: 10000, maximumAge: 0 }
          );
        },
        onFailure: (err) => {
          updateStatus(" MQTT connection failed: " + JSON.stringify(err));
          console.error("MQTT connection failed:", err);
        },

        userName: creds.accessKeyId,
        password: creds.sessionToken
      };

      mqttClient.connect(connectOptions);
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

What this does:

  • After connecting, subscribes to mobile/location topic

  • Displays incoming messages in the new Incoming Messages box, timestamped and formatted

  • Still publishes your current geolocation to the same topic once on connect

  • Logs useful events and errors to console and status area

Note again on authentication:

This approach might still have connection/auth issues because Paho MQTT JS client doesnt do AWS SigV4 signing automatically. If you face connection errors, consider using the AWS IoT Device SDK v2 for browsers, which handles signing properly.

The resource was blocked due to MIME type (text/plain) mismatch (X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff).

This means the CDN link you are using for Paho MQTT is serving a wrong MIME type (text/plain instead of application/javascript), so the browser blocks loading the script.
Because of this, your script fails with Uncaught ReferenceError: Paho is not defined.

How to fix this:

  1. Use a working CDN link for Paho MQTT that sets correct headers
    Try this official Eclipse Paho CDN link instead:

This is the same version you originally used and should work fine.

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>IoT Location Test</title>
  <script src="https://sdk.amazonaws.com/js/aws-sdk-2.814.0.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/eclipse/paho.mqtt.javascript@v1.1.0/src/paho-mqtt.min.js"></script>
  <style>
    body { font-family: sans-serif; padding: 20px; }
    #status { margin-bottom: 10px; color: green; }
    #messages { border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 10px; max-height: 150px; overflow: auto; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h2> AWS IoT Location Sender</h2>
  <div id="status">Loading...</div>
  <div id="messages">(No messages)</div>

  <script>
    const REGION = "us-east-1";
    const IDENTITY_POOL_ID = "us-east-1:018326cf-26a9-4a3e-88e4-d64a4b61bdc2";
    const IOT_ENDPOINT = "a85vmpn2frq7e-ats.iot.us-east-1.amazonaws.com";

    const statusEl = document.getElementById("status");
    const messagesEl = document.getElementById("messages");

    const log = (msg) => {
      statusEl.textContent = msg;
      console.log(msg);
    };

    const addMessage = (msg) => {
      const div = document.createElement("div");
      div.textContent = msg;
      messagesEl.appendChild(div);
    };

    AWS.config.region = REGION;
    AWS.config.credentials = new AWS.CognitoIdentityCredentials({
      IdentityPoolId: IDENTITY_POOL_ID
    });

    log("Requesting AWS credentials...");
    AWS.config.credentials.get((err) => {
      if (err) return log(" Credential error: " + err.message);

      log(" AWS credentials ready.");
      const creds = AWS.config.credentials;
      const clientId = "client-" + Math.floor(Math.random() * 100000);

      const client = new Paho.MQTT.Client(
        IOT_ENDPOINT,
        443,
        "/mqtt",
        clientId
      );

      client.onConnectionLost = (e) => log(" Lost connection: " + e.errorMessage);
      client.onMessageArrived = (msg) => {
        const payload = msg.payloadString;
        addMessage(` ${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}: ${payload}`);
      };

      client.connect({
        useSSL: true,
        mqttVersion: 4,
        userName: creds.accessKeyId,
        password: creds.sessionToken,
        onSuccess: () => {
          log(" Connected to AWS IoT");
          client.subscribe("mobile/location");

          if (!navigator.geolocation) return log(" Geolocation not supported");
          navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
            (pos) => {
              const payload = JSON.stringify({
                lat: pos.coords.latitude,
                lon: pos.coords.longitude,
                time: new Date().toISOString()
              });
              const message = new Paho.MQTT.Message(payload);
              message.destinationName = "mobile/location";
              client.send(message);
              log(" Location sent.");
            },
            (err) => log(" Geolocation error: " + err.message)
          );
        },
        onFailure: (e) => log(" Connection failed: " + e.errorMessage)
      });
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Bonus Fix: document.getElementById(...) is null
